text:
Outlier. I am sure most people who learn about Data Science or statistics know about it. Wikipedia defines an outlier as extreme data or data that differ significantly.
I often ask people 'What do you think about outlier?' and 'What should you do with outlier?'. Many answered that outlier is distracting and need to be removed.
In truth, the outlier is as interesting as any other data. What you do with the outlier of course depends on what context your question is. Nevertheless, the outlier is as important as any other data. For that case, I try to create a post to tell outlier importance.
Happy Reading!
#data #datascience #datascientist #dataanalyst #dataanalysis #cornelly
TOWARDSDATASCIENCE.COM
Outlier — Why is it important?

text: I have a project that will hopefully interest a pro-police reform data scientist or someone just looking for some one-of-a-kind previously secret data to practice on. Through the California Public Records Act, I was able to acquire the metadata from the Long Beach Police Department's use of a disappearing text messaging service called Tiger Text. The city denied using the program to the press, but eventually, the ACLU got them to admit it. The city claimed it was only used for routine communications and not for investigative communications. They even paid a well-connected local law firm a lot of money for an independent report that was just a rehashing of the police's lies but with… More

I hope you like it :)

text:
Hi all,
A lot of people use Keras to train their deep learning models.
When you train models you need to evaluate them as well but choosing a good metric can be tricky.
- you need to understand which metrics are already available in Keras and tf.keras and how to use them,
- in many situations, you need to define your own custom metric because the metric you are looking for doesn’t ship with Keras.
- sometimes you want to monitor model performance by looking at charts like ROC curve or Confusion Matrix after every epoch.
We've put together an article that explains all that and more.
I hope, this will be helpful to you!
https://neptune.ai/blog/keras-metrics?utm_source=facebook&utm_medium=post-in-group&utm_campaign=blog-keras-metrics&utm_content=BigDataPakistan

Hey guys! I hope everyone here is having a safe quarantine!
Over the past couple of weeks, I’ve been working on a project to create a neural network from scratch.
Recently I’ve been able to get some nice results from the algorithm, and I wrote an article for Medium documenting the whole experience.
The article is great for anyone wanting to learn more about how neural nets work!
The goal of the article is to explain the basic workings of NNs and how they can achieve incredible results. All of this by coding one yourself!
In the article there are a bunch of code snippets and notes that can help guide you to create your own network! It might be fun for a weekend project…
To anyone who might be interested, you can find the article at:
https://towardsdatascience.com/creating-a-neural-network-from-scratch-302e8fb61703?source=friends_link&sk=8afd0cc293f05e9a3e42875b24005de9
And the GitHub repository at:
https://github.com/jzsiggy/NN-from-scratch
Feel free to clone, fork, copy or ask me about the code (and article) if you wish!

text:
Hello, I am interesting it to find the bias of a ML model (i.e. RF) when it perform prediction on some data.. I did not find how can we quantify the bias of a ML model. I was reading a blog which states the following. Could someone plz interpret it for me what does it mean to find the bias of a model?
Suppose that you have a regression problem and you are interested in measuring RMSE. Imagine that, for your data, there is some “true” RMSE value that a particular model could achieve. The bias is the difference between what the resampling procedure estimates your RMSE to be for that model and the true RMSE. Basically, you can think of it as accuracy of estimation. The precision measures how variable the result is. Some types of resampling have higher bias than others and the same is true for precision.
